  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Spring Hill is one of Brisbane's most unusual inner-city suburbs. Sitting directly north of the CBD grid, it is a tight mix of workers cottages, terrace houses, restored Queenslanders and a growing layer of apartments that spans from 1990s utilitarian stock through to contemporary mid-rise. It offers something most inner-city precincts cannot: the ability to walk to the CBD in fifteen minutes through streets that have genuine architectural heritage rather than redevelopment-era uniformity. That combination has been drawing an increasingly intentional buyer over the past five years.</p>

      <p>The Royal Brisbane and Women's Hospital to the north and St Andrew's Hospital on Wickham Terrace give Spring Hill a permanent professional buyer base that is not tied to seasonal market cycles in the way family-driven suburbs are. Healthcare workers make up a consistent segment of both the owner-occupier character cottage market and the apartment market, and their purchasing decisions are often connected to contract start dates and hospital rotation schedules rather than school term calendars.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who is buying in Spring Hill</h2>
      <p>Professionals who have decided they want to walk to work are the core buyer in Spring Hill's character cottage market. These are people who have made a deliberate lifestyle choice to reduce commute friction and live in a suburb with genuine heritage character rather than an apartment tower. They are typically well-resourced buyers who have done their research on the suburb and know what they are looking for. When a well-presented workers cottage or restored Queenslander hits the market at a defensible price, these buyers respond quickly.</p>

      <p>A second significant segment is the downsizer from inner-east family suburbs, often from Hawthorne, New Farm or Paddington, who wants city-edge living with a character context rather than a high-rise apartment experience. These buyers are often selling a family home at the same time and are bringing meaningful equity into the purchase. They value the Wickham Park open space, the proximity to the CBD cultural precinct, and the suburb's sense of established character over the polish of a new-build. The apartment market in Spring Hill also attracts interstate investors who understand the suburb's proximity to two major hospitals and the CBD as a structural yield and growth argument.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What drives value in Spring Hill</h2>
      <p>Character authenticity is the primary value driver in the detached home segment. A Spring Hill workers cottage that has been sympathetically restored, where the original facade, ceiling heights and period detail are intact and the interior has been updated without erasing the home's identity, will consistently outperform a home of similar footprint where the character has been stripped. The buyers who target Spring Hill are specifically choosing it over new-build suburbs, and they are paying for the authenticity of the character. Compromise that and you compromise the premium.</p>

      <p>In the apartment segment, building age and management quality are the primary determinants. Well-managed buildings with healthy sinking funds, north or east-facing aspects and at least one secure car space trade significantly above older stock with deferred maintenance or opaque body corporate records. The Spring Hill apartment buyer is experienced and will ask for disclosure documentation as standard. Any building with pending special levies or significant maintenance issues will face buyer resistance that pricing alone cannot overcome.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Preparing your Spring Hill property for sale</h2>
      <p>For character homes, the preparation is about presenting the authenticity of the property clearly. Professional photography that captures the heritage streetscape, the character of the interior and any outdoor space is essential. In Spring Hill's narrow streets, the front facade photograph is often the first and most important impression. A freshly painted exterior, clean pathways and a tidy garden signal care and respect for the property. Inside, declutter and style in a way that honours the character of the architecture rather than imposing a generic contemporary finish over it.</p>

      <p>For apartments, gather body corporate records, levy schedules and sinking fund documentation before the campaign launches. Buyers will request these during due diligence and a prompt, complete disclosure sets a professional tone for the negotiation. Any known maintenance issues should either be addressed before the campaign or clearly priced into the listing strategy.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Best time to sell in Spring Hill</h2>
      <p>Spring Hill's hospital precinct buyer base gives it a more even year-round demand profile than family-oriented suburbs. Healthcare workers and CBD professionals are not constrained by school term calendars in the same way family buyers are. That said, the two strongest market windows are autumn (March to May) and spring (September to November). The autumn window captures buyers who have been active through the previous spring and summer without finding the right property and bring genuine urgency into the new year. The spring window generates the highest open home volumes and the most competitive buyer conditions across inner Brisbane. A well-prepared Spring Hill campaign launched in either window is unlikely to sit idle for long if the pricing is defensible and the presentation is strong.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How long does it take to sell in Spring Hill</h2>
      <p>Well-presented Spring Hill cottages typically go under contract within 25 to 40 days. The detached home market is thin: there are not many sales per year and buyers who have identified Spring Hill as a target suburb maintain active alerts and respond quickly when something suitable comes to market. Apartments in the suburb track 30 to 50 days depending on building age, view and amenity. The growth rates on both house and unit stock in Spring Hill have been among the strongest in inner Brisbane through 2025 and into 2026, which reflects the increasing recognition of the suburb's walkability and character proposition. Sellers who price on recent comparable evidence and invest in professional presentation will find their buyer without a prolonged campaign.</p>

